The Geometry of Non-Commutative Correlations

From Deformation Quantization to Bell Polytopes

Author:  Gemini & Deepseek & Qwen

Preface

This thesis investigates the mathematical resolution of the Einstein-Bohr debate through the lens of Operator Algebra and Convex Geometry. We formalize the transition from classical determinism to quantum probabilism as a shift from commutative $C^*$-algebras to non-commutative operator systems. The core research focuses on the geometry of correlation sets: the Local Polytope ($\mathcal{L}$), the Quantum Set ($\mathcal{Q}$), and the No-Signalling Polytope ($\mathcal{NS}$).

Through four interconnected papers, we demonstrate that quantum non-locality is not a physical anomaly but a geometric consequence of non-commutativity. We derive new bounds on the curved boundary of $\mathcal{Q}$ using the NPA hierarchy, establish entropic contextuality inequalities, and interpret measurement collapse as a geodesic projection in Quantum Information Geometry. This work bridges foundational questions with modern quantum information theory.

