Appendix A: Detailed Calculations for Paper 1

A.1 Covariance Matrix of TMSV

The two-mode squeezing operator $\hat{S}_{AB}(r) = \exp(r(\hat{a}\hat{b} - \hat{a}^\dagger\hat{b}^\dagger))$ acts on annihilation operators as:
\hat{S}_{AB}^\dagger(r) \hat{a} \hat{S}_{AB}(r) = \hat{a}\cosh r + \hat{b}^\dagger \sinh r 


\hat{S}_{AB}^\dagger(r) \hat{b} \hat{S}_{AB}(r) = \hat{b}\cosh r + \hat{a}^\dagger \sinh r 

In the quadrature basis $\hat{\mathbf{R}} = (\hat{q}_A, \hat{p}_A, \hat{q}_B, \hat{p}_B)^T$, with $\hat{q} = \sqrt{\frac{\hbar}{2}}(\hat{a}+\hat{a}^\dagger)$, $\hat{p} = -i\sqrt{\frac{\hbar}{2}}(\hat{a}-\hat{a}^\dagger)$, the covariance matrix $\Sigma_{ij} = \frac{1}{2}\langle \hat{R}_i\hat{R}_j + \hat{R}_j\hat{R}_i \rangle$ is:
 \Sigma = \frac{\hbar}{2} \begin{pmatrix}
\cosh(2r) & 0 & \sinh(2r) & 0 \\
0 & \cosh(2r) & 0 & -\sinh(2r) \\
\sinh(2r) & 0 & \cosh(2r) & 0 \\
0 & -\sinh(2r) & 0 & \cosh(2r)
\end{pmatrix} 

A.2 Wigner Function of TMSV

For a Gaussian state with zero mean and covariance matrix $\Sigma$, the Wigner function is:
W(\mathbf{z}) = \frac{1}{(2\pi)^2 \sqrt{\det \Sigma}} \exp\left( -\frac{1}{2} \mathbf{z}^T \Sigma^{-1} \mathbf{z} \right) 

Since $\det \Sigma = (\hbar/2)^4$, we have $\sqrt{\det \Sigma} = (\hbar/2)^2$. The inverse is:
 \Sigma^{-1} = \frac{2}{\hbar} \begin{pmatrix}
\cosh(2r)I_2 & -\sinh(2r)Z_2 \\
-\sinh(2r)Z_2 & \cosh(2r)I_2
\end{pmatrix} 

Therefore:
W(q_A,p_A,q_B,p_B) = \frac{1}{\pi^2 \hbar^2} \exp\left[ -\frac{1}{\hbar} \left( \cosh(2r)(q_A^2+p_A^2+q_B^2+p_B^2) - 2\sinh(2r)(q_A q_B - p_A p_B) \right) \right] 

A.3 Characteristic Function

The characteristic function is the Fourier transform of the Wigner function:
\chi(\lambda_A, \lambda_B) = \int e^{i(\lambda_A q_A + \lambda_A' p_A + \lambda_B q_B + \lambda_B' p_B)} W(\mathbf{z}) \, d^4z 

In complex notation $\lambda = \lambda_q + i\lambda_p$, this becomes:
\chi(\lambda_A, \lambda_B) = \exp\left( -\frac{1}{2} \left[ (|\lambda_A|^2 + |\lambda_B|^2) \cosh(2r) + (\lambda_A \lambda_B + \lambda_A^* \lambda_B^*) \sinh(2r) \right] \right) 

A.4 Correlation Function for Displaced Parity

Using $\hat{\Pi}(\alpha) = \int \frac{d^2\lambda}{\pi} e^{\alpha\lambda^* - \alpha^*\lambda} \hat{D}(\lambda)$ and $\langle \hat{D}(\lambda) \rangle = \chi(\lambda)$, we have:
E(\alpha,\beta) = \int \frac{d^2\lambda_A}{\pi} \frac{d^2\lambda_B}{\pi} e^{\alpha\lambda_A^* - \alpha^*\lambda_A} e^{\beta\lambda_B^* - \beta^*\lambda_B} \chi(\lambda_A, \lambda_B) 

Completing the square in the Gaussian integral yields:
E(\alpha,\beta) = \frac{1}{\cosh(2r)} \exp\left( -2|\alpha|^2 - 2|\beta|^2 + 2\tanh(2r)(\alpha\beta + \alpha^*\beta^*) \right) 

